/MINOR/PATCH, but preserve it unchanged if you mention a\nresulting version string.\nYour output is a recommendation — final version application is confirmed manually.\n\n\n**Approach**: 0. Check file category counts: if Documentation/Test/Code/Config counts are all 0 despite a\n   non-zero \"Total modified files\", the staged changes consist entirely of workflow artifact\n   files (`.ai_workflow/`). Identify the actual file path(s) from the diff sample or git\n   context and treat them as internal tooling changes (→ typically patch).\n1. Read CHANGELOG.md [Unreleased] section to understand all documented pending changes\n2. Review git commit messages for conventional commit types (feat, fix, BREAKING CHANGE)\n3. Examine the provided git diff and changed file list, categorising changes by project area:\n   - `config/` changes → configuration or schema updates (potential minor/patch)\n   - `src/` changes → code/API changes (potential major/minor)\n   - `test/` or `src/__tests__/` changes → test coverage improvements (patch)\n   - `docs/` or `*.md` changes → documentation updates (patch)\n   - `scripts/` changes → tooling/maintenance (patch/chore)\n   - `.ai_workflow/` only → internal artifacts (patch; see step 0)\n4. Consult the project's versioning guidance in this order: `CHANGELOG.md`,\n   `CONTRIBUTING.md`, `README.md`, `docs/guides/DEVELOPER_GUIDE.md`,\n   `docs/api/core/version.md`, and `docs/architecture/VERSION_TIMELINE.md` if present\n5. Identify the highest-severity change type: breaking → MAJOR, new feature → MINOR, fix/docs → PATCH\n6. Determine minimum required version bump based on findings\n   - Pre-release suffixes do not upgrade severity on their own\n   - Build metadata does not affect precedence or bump classification\n7. Provide clear reasoning citing specific changes from CHANGELOG.md or commits\nNote: This recommendation requires manual confirmation before the version is applied.\n\n\nBump Type: [major|minor|patch]\nReasoning: [2-3 sentence expl